const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How long does a commercial roof replacement typically take?',
    answer: 'Timelines vary by facility size and system type. A typical 50,000 sq. ft. warehouse re-roof runs two to three weeks once tear-off and weather windows are factored in. We commit to a guaranteed phased schedule during the assessment so building operations can continue during work. For the trade-offs between repair, overlay, and full replacement see our breakdown of commercial roof repair vs replacement at /blog/commercial-roof-repair-vs-replacement/.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What does a commercial roof cost per square foot?',
    answer: 'Installed cost on a low-slope commercial roof typically runs $4 to $12 per square foot for single-ply membrane systems (TPO, EPDM), $8 to $10 for built-up roofing (BUR), and $16 to $22 for standing-seam metal panels. The spread is driven by tear-off scope, insulation R-value, deck condition, attachment method, parapet and penetration count, and whether the project requires phased off-hours work. The executive assessment delivers a per-square-foot range against your specific facility — not a generic number off a price sheet.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What does a commercial roofer actually do that\'s different from a residential one?',
    answer: 'Commercial roofers work on flat and low-slope decks where the membrane (not the shingle) is the waterproofing layer, where roof-mounted HVAC and conduit penetrations matter more than aesthetics, and where the project has to integrate with active building operations. The materials are different (single-ply TPO/EPDM/PVC, modified bitumen, BUR, standing-seam metal), the warranties are different (NDL coverage from GAF, Firestone, Carlisle, Owens Corning), the safety regime is different (OSHA-certified fall protection, JHA per-zone), and the procurement process is different (RFQ, phased schedule, payment milestones). Residential roofers handle steep-slope shingle work — different system, different code, different decision-makers.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is an NDL warranty and why do I need it?',
    answer: 'An NDL (No Dollar Limit) warranty is the manufacturer\'s commitment to repair or replace your roofing system without a financial cap on labor or material costs through the warranty term — typically 20 to 30 years on commercial single-ply systems. Standard warranties cap exposure; NDL warranties don\'t. For a multi-million-dollar roof on a Class A property, that uncapped exposure is the single most important paragraph in the warranty packet. NDL coverage is only available through manufacturer-certified installers — including GAF Master Elite, Firestone Licensed, and Owens Corning Platinum contractors.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the 25% rule for roofing?',
    answer: 'The 25% rule is a decision heuristic: if more than roughly 25% of the roof surface is compromised (active leaks, saturated insulation, failed seams, structural deck issues), full replacement usually costs less over a 10-year horizon than repeated repairs. The rule is a starting point, not a verdict — the executive assessment looks at remaining membrane life, deck condition, total damaged area, and warranty status to give you the actual repair-vs-replace recommendation backed by core samples and infrared scan data.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do I tell if a commercial roofer is being honest with me?',
    answer: 'Five things to verify before signing a commercial contract: (1) state license and bond on file in your state — not just a contractor card; (2) workers\' comp and general liability certificates dated within 30 days, naming your property as additional insured; (3) manufacturer certification status verifiable on the manufacturer\'s site (GAF, Firestone, Owens Corning all publish certified-installer directories); (4) a written scope with specific membrane brand, thickness in mils, attachment method, and warranty term — not "premium TPO"; and (5) reluctance to demand large up-front payment. Anyone insisting on full payment in advance, guaranteeing an insurance claim before the carrier approves it, or refusing to put a written scope in your hands is a red flag.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can you perform work without interrupting our business operations?',
    answer: 'Yes — phased off-hours installation is standard practice on our commercial portfolio. Our hot-air welded TPO seams produce no fumes, which makes daytime adjacent work feasible on retail and multi-tenant properties. For 24/7 operations like distribution centers, we sequence tear-off and install in zones that follow the building\'s operational rhythm — overnight crews on the dock-side, daytime crews on inactive areas. Documentation of the phasing plan is part of the executive assessment deliverable.',
  },
];

